AGREEMENT BETWEEN LEORA HOME HEALTH LLC AND DOTFUN, LLC
This Agreement ("Agreement") is made and entered into as of February 10, 2025, and shall 
commence on February 10, 2025, and continue indefinitely unless earlier terminated as provided 
herein, by and between Leora Home Health LLC ("Client") and DotFun, LLC ("Service Provider"), 
collectively referred to as the "Parties."
1. Scope of Services
1.1 DotFun's Responsibilities
DotFun agrees to provide the following services to Leora Home Health LLC under the 10% 
package:
Look Good
Website design and development
Ongoing website maintenance and page creation
Template creation for social, email, and ads
Support for event assets
Creative direction
Feel Good
GoHighLevel implementation with email & SMS support
Document Ref: BB05DEE5-B89D-4B4A-8AAC-670F13B80C8D 2/6
SEO & content strategy
Limited content development (1 blog/month)
Reporting
Persona development
Conversion Rate Optimization (CRO)
1.2 Conditional Expansion of Services
If Leora Home Health LLC achieves a profitability of over $1M per year, DotFun agrees to expand 
services while maintaining the 10% profit share model to include:
Look Good (Expanded)
Website design and development
Ongoing website maintenance and page creation
Template creation for social, email, and ads
Support for event assets
Creative direction
Video production
Event design
Graphic/visual design
Feel Good (Expanded)
GoHighLevel implementation with email & SMS support
SEO & content strategy
Content development for blogs, resources, and reports
Media planning and forecasting
Document Ref: BB05DEE5-B89D-4B4A-8AAC-670F13B80C8D 3/6
Paid advertising/paid social
Assistance with in-person events and campaigns
Performance analytics and reporting
1.3 Client Responsibilities
Leora Home Health LLC agrees to:
Provide DotFun with access to all necessary materials, internal stakeholders, and 
documentation.
Ensure timely feedback and approvals on deliverables, understanding that not providing 
feedback will push deadlines back.
2. Term & Termination
2.2 Termination
This Agreement may be terminated under the following conditions:
By mutual written agreement of both Parties.
By either Party for material breach, provided written notice is given and a 30-day cure period 
has passed without resolution.
In the event of bankruptcy, insolvency, or dissolution of either Party.
In cases of fraud, willful misconduct, or illegal activities.
Effect of Termination: Upon termination, the Parties shall fulfill any outstanding obligations, 
including payments due, and shall promptly return any materials, property, or confidential 
information belonging to the other Party.
3. Compensation & Payment Terms
3.1 Payment Structure
Document Ref: BB05DEE5-B89D-4B4A-8AAC-670F13B80C8D 4/6
Compensation shall be 10% of Leora Home Health LLC’s net profits in perpetuity unless 
amended by mutual written agreement.
Payments shall be made quarterly in alignment with leadership distributions at Leora Home 
Health LLC.
Additional fees for out-of-scope work must be pre-approved in writing.
3.2 Profit-Based Service Expansion
When Leora Home Health LLC achieves over $1M in annual profitability, the expanded services 
listed in Section 1.2 will be included under the existing 10% profit share model.
4. Confidentiality & Intellectual Property
4.1 Confidentiality
Both Parties agree to keep all confidential or proprietary information obtained under this 
Agreement strictly confidential.
4.2 Intellectual Property
Any intellectual property created solely by DotFun shall remain its exclusive property.
Any intellectual property developed specifically for Leora Home Health LLC shall be 
transferred upon full payment.
5. Indemnification & Liability
5.1 Indemnification
Each Party agrees to indemnify and hold harmless the other from any claims, liabilities, or 
damages resulting from gross negligence or willful misconduct.
5.2 Limitation of Liability
Neither Party shall be liable for indirect, incidental, or consequential damages arising from this 
Agreement.
Document Ref: BB05DEE5-B89D-4B4A-8AAC-670F13B80C8D 5/6
6. Force Majeure
Neither Party shall be liable for any failure or delay in performing its obligations under this 
Agreement due to a Force Majeure Event. Such events include, but are not limited to, natural 
disasters, war, civil unrest, government actions, pandemics, and other circumstances beyond the 
control of the Parties. The affected Party shall provide prompt written notice and shall take 
reasonable steps to mitigate the impact. If the Force Majeure Event continues beyond 60 days, 
either Party may terminate the Agreement without liability.
7. Audit Rights
Leora Home Health LLC shall maintain complete financial records necessary to calculate

schema.text:
AMENDMENT TO THE OPERATING AGREEMENT OF LEORA HOME HEALTH LLC
This Amendment to the Operating Agreement (the "Amendment") of Leora Home Health LLC (the "Company") is made and entered into as of February 6, 2025, by and between the Members of the Company, as identified in the Operating Agreement originally executed on September 20, 2024.
RECITALS WHEREAS, the Members executed an Operating Agreement governing the management, ownership, and operations of the Company;
WHEREAS, the Members wish to amend the provisions related to the ownership of intellectual property to clarify that software not specifically created for Leora Home Health LLC shall not be considered the property of the Company;
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and covenants contained herein and in the Operating Agreement, the Members agree as follows:
AMENDMENT
Modification of Article XV: Ownership of Intellectual Property
Article XV of the Operating Agreement is hereby amended and restated as follows:
Ownership of Intellectual Property:
All intellectual property created, developed, or acquired by the Members in connection with the business of the Company, including but not limited to trademarks, copyrights, patents, software, and business processes, shall be the sole property of the Company if it is specifically created, developed, or acquired by the Members for use by the Company.
Notwithstanding the foregoing, any software developed, created, or acquired by a Member that is not specifically developed, created, or acquired for Leora Home Health LLC shall not be considered the property of the Company. Ownership of such software shall remain with the Member or entity that developed or acquired it. This includes, but is not limited to, software developed by a Member for other business ventures, unrelated projects, or companies owned by a Member outside of Leora Home Health LLC.
In the event that software originally developed outside the scope of Leora Home Health LLC is later incorporated into the Company’s business operations, the terms of use, licensing, or transfer of ownership shall be subject to a separate written agreement between the Members.
Effect of Amendment
Except as expressly modified by this Amendment, all terms and conditions of the original Operating Agreement shall remain in full force and effect.
If any provision of this Amendment conflicts with the terms of the original Operating Agreement, the provisions of this Amendment shall control.
Governing Law
This Amendment shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Texas.
SIGNATURES IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned Members have executed this Amendment as of the date first written above.

"""Generated message classes for container version v1.

Builds and manages container-based applications, powered by the open source
Kubernetes technology.
"""
# NOTE: This file is autogenerated and should not be edited by hand.

from __future__ import absolute_import

from apitools.base.protorpclite import messages as _messages
from apitools.base.py import encoding
from apitools.base.py import extra_types


package = 'container'


class AcceleratorConfig(_messages.Message):
  r"""AcceleratorConfig represents a Hardware Accelerator request.

  Fields:
    acceleratorCount: The number of the accelerator cards exposed to an
      instance.
    acceleratorType: The accelerator type resource name. List of supported
      accelerators [here](https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/gpus)
    gpuDriverInstallationConfig: The configuration for auto installation of
      GPU driver.
    gpuPartitionSize: Size of partitions to create on the GPU. Valid values
      are described in the NVIDIA [mig user
      guide](https://docs.nvidia.com/datacenter/tesla/mig-user-
      guide/#partitioning).
    gpuSharingConfig: The configuration for GPU sharing options.
  """

  acceleratorCount = _messages.IntegerField(1)
  acceleratorType = _messages.StringField(2)
  gpuDriverInstallationConfig = _messages.MessageField('GPUDriverInstallationConfig', 3)
  gpuPartitionSize = _messages.StringField(4)
  gpuSharingConfig = _messages.MessageField('GPUSharingConfig', 5)


class AdditionalIPRangesConfig(_messages.Message):
  r"""AdditionalIPRangesConfig is the configuration for individual additional
  subnetwork attached to the cluster

  Fields:
    podIpv4RangeNames: List of secondary ranges names within this subnetwork
      that can be used for pod IPs. Example1: gke-pod-range1 Example2: gke-
      pod-range1,gke-pod-range2
    subnetwork: Name of the subnetwork. This can be the full path of the
      subnetwork or just the name. Example1: my-subnet Example2: projects/gke-
      project/regions/us-central1/subnetworks/my-subnet
  """

  podIpv4RangeNames = _messages.StringField(1, repeated=True)
  subnetwork = _messages.StringField(2)


class AdditionalNodeNetworkConfig(_messages.Message):
  r"""AdditionalNodeNetworkConfig is the configuration for additional node
  networks within the NodeNetworkConfig message

  Fields:
    network: Name of the VPC where the additional interface belongs
    subnetwork: Name of the subnetwork where the additional interface belongs
  """

  network = _messages.StringField(1)
  subnetwork = _messages.StringField(2)


class AdditionalPodNetworkConfig(_messages.Message):
  r"""AdditionalPodNetworkConfig is the configuration for additional pod
  networks within the NodeNetworkConfig message

  Fields:
    maxPodsPerNode: The maximum number of pods per node which use this pod
      network.
    networkAttachment: The name of the network attachment for pods to
      communicate to; cannot be specified along with subnetwork or
      secondary_pod_range.
    secondaryPodRange: The name of the secondary range on the subnet which
      provides IP address for this pod range.
    subnetwork: Name of the subnetwork where the additional pod network
      belongs.
  """

  maxPodsPerNode = _messages.MessageField('MaxPodsConstraint', 1)
  networkAttachment = _messages.StringField(2)
  secondaryPodRange = _messages.StringField(3)
  subnetwork = _messages.StringField(4)


class AdditionalPodRangesConfig(_messages.Message):
  r"""AdditionalPodRangesConfig is the configuration for additional pod
  secondary ranges supporting the ClusterUpdate message.

  Fields:
    podRangeInfo: Output only. Information for additional pod range.
    podRangeNames: Name for pod secondary ipv4 range which has the actual
      range defined ahead.
  """

  podRangeInfo = _messages.MessageField('RangeInfo', 1, repeated=True)
  podRangeNames = _messages.StringField(2, repeated=True)

    cloudRunConfig: Configuration for the Cloud Run addon, which allows the
      user to use a managed Knative service.
    configConnectorConfig: Configuration for the ConfigConnector add-on, a
      Kubernetes extension to manage hosted GCP services through the
      Kubernetes API
    dnsCacheConfig: Configuration for NodeLocalDNS, a dns cache running on
      cluster nodes
    gcePersistentDiskCsiDriverConfig: Configuration for the Compute Engine
      Persistent Disk CSI driver.
    gcpFilestoreCsiDriverConfig: Configuration for the GCP Filestore CSI
      driver.
    gcsFuseCsiDriverConfig: Configuration for the Cloud Storage Fuse CSI
      driver.

OPERATING AGREEMENT
FOR
____________________________________________________
A SINGLE MEMBER-MANAGED LIMITED LIABILITY COMPANY
ARTICLE I
Company Formation
1.1. FORMATION. The  member  has  formed  a  Limited  Liability  Company  (the  "Company")
according to the laws of the state in which the Company was formed. This operating agreement
is entered into and effective as of the date it is adopted by the member.
1.2. REGISTERED AGENT. The name and location of the Company’s registered agent will be
stated in the company’s formation documents.
1.3. TERM. The Company will continue perpetually unless:
(a) The sole member resolves to dissolve; 
(b) Any event which causes the Company’s business to become unlawful; 
(c) The death, resignation, expulsion, bankruptcy, retirement of the sole member or
the occurrence of any other event that terminates the continued membership of a
member of the Company; or 
(d) Any other event causing dissolution of the Company under applicable state laws.
1.4. CONTINUANCE OF COMPANY. In the event of an occurrence described in Section 1.3(c),
the Company will expire and may be administratively dissolved.
1.5. BUSINESS PURPOSE. The Company will conduct any lawful business deemed appropriate in
carrying out the Company’s objectives.
1.6. PRINCIPAL PLACE OF BUSINESS.  The Company’s principal place of business will be
stated in the formation documents, or as later selected by the member.
1.7. THE MEMBER. The name and residential address of the sole member is listed in Certification
of Member section of this agreement.
Single Member Operating Agreement – Page 1 of 6              

1.8. ADMISSION OF ADDITIONAL MEMBERS. Additional members may only be admitted to
the Company through a Certificate of New Membership issuance by the company of new
interest in the Company or as otherwise provided in this agreement.
ARTICLE II
Capital Contributions
2.1. INITIAL CONTRIBUTIONS. The member will initially contribute capital to the Company, as
described in Exhibit 1 attached to this agreement. The agreed total value of such property and
cash is ____________________________.
2.2. ADDITIONAL CONTRIBUTIONS. Except as provided in ARTICLE 6.2, no member will be
obligated to make any additional contribution to the Company's capital.
ARTICLE III
Profits, Losses and Distributions
3.1. PROFITS/LOSSES. For financial accounting and tax purposes, the Company's net profits or
net losses will be determined on an annual basis. These profits and losses will be allocated to
the member as set forth in this agreement below, as amended, and in accordance with Treasury
Regulation 1.704-1.
3.2. DISTRIBUTIONS. The member will determine and distribute available funds annually or as
they see fit. “Available funds” refers to the net cash of the Company available after expenses
and  liabilities  are  paid.  Upon  liquidation  of  the  Company,  distributions  will  be  made  in
accordance with the positive capital account balances or pursuant to Treasury Regulation 1.704-
l(b)(2)(ii)(b) (2). To the extent the member has a negative capital account balance, there will be
a qualified income offset, as set forth in Treasury Regulation 1.704-l(b)(2)(ii)(d).
ARTICLE IV
Management
4.1. MANAGEMENT OF THE BUSINESS.  The member is responsible for the  management of
the Company.  
4.2. MEMBERS. The liability of the member will be limited according to state law. 
4.3. POWERS OF  MEMB ERS. The member is authorized on the Company's behalf to make
decisions as to: 
(a) the sale, development, lease, or other disposition of the Company's assets; 
(b) the purchase or other acquisition of other assets; 
(c) the management of all or any part of the Company's assets; 
(d) the borrowing of money and the granting of security interests in the Company’s
assets; 
(e) the pre-payment, refinancing, or extension of any loan affecting the Company’s
assets; 
Single Member Operating Agreement – Page 2 of 6              

(f) the compromise or release of any of the Company's claims or debts; and 
(g) the  employment  of  persons,  firms,  or  corporations  for  the  operation  and
management of the Company's business.
The member is further authorized to execute and deliver:
(w) all contracts, conveyances, assignments leases, sub-leases, franchise agreements,
licensing agreements, management contracts and maintenance contracts covering
or affecting Company assets; 
(x) all checks, drafts, and other orders for the payment of the Company's funds; 
(y) all promissory notes, loans, security agreements, and other similar documents;
and 
(z) all other instruments of any other kind relating to the Company's affairs.
4.4. NOMINEE. Title to the Company's assets must be held in the Company's name or in the name
of any nominee that the member may designate. Pursuant to the powers listed in Section 4.3, the
member has the  power to enter into a nominee agreement with any such person, and such
agreement may contain provisions indemnifying the nominee, except for his or her will

BizAidSM Business Orientation
CITY OF AUSTIN
SMALL BUSINESS DIVISION
Dear Entrepreneur:
Welcome to the City of Austin’s BizAid SM Business Orientation hosted by the Small Business Program.
Our objective is to help you understand the opportunities and challenges of business ownership and where to find no cost or low-cost assistance. Through the BizAidSM Program, we provide assistance in reviewing your business and marketing plans
and guidance with the mechanics of getting started. This orientation is just one tool offered by the Small Business Division. We are committed to ensuring that Austin’s small businesses have access to resources needed to succeed in today’s competitive environment. Our organization is always searching for the latest information and assistance that help local businesses grow and prosper. Check our website regularly for information, classes, and events that can help strengthen your business.
Please complete a brief evaluation at the close of today’s session. Your feedback is valuable and will serve as the basis for enhancements of our services.
Let us know of your small business successes throughout your entrepreneurial journey. We look forward to celebrating with you!
Best Wishes,
Xavier Zarate, Small Business Manager Economic Development Department City of Austin
512 974 2502
xavier.zarate@austintexas.gov www.SmallBizAustin.org
@AustinEconDev Facebook, Twitter, Youtube

According to the Bureau of Labor and Statistics, approximately 50% of small businesses are still open after five years.
According to multiple industry surveys, entrepreneurs are twice as likely to successfully launch a business, expand a business, and obtain commercial lending if they complete a business plan.

Our Services

BizAidSM  Business Orientation
A general overview of starting or growing a business in Austin. In this session, you will be informed of key questions to consider when developing your business and helpful resources to take you to the next level. Pre-recorded is also available. 
BizOpen: Commercial Property Requirements
One-on-one assistance navigating the City of Austin’s development and permitting process through classroom and webinar orientations.
Business Coaching
www.peoplefund.org/intake
One-on-one review of business plan, marketing plan, financial readiness assessment, and business management technical assistance plus access to industry and market research. You must attend our BizAid Business Orientation to qualify for a business coach appointment.
Who qualifies?
For-profit business located within the Austin city limits
Non-profit or located outside Austin city limits but within the Austin metro area, limited to one appointment
Industry Research: AtoZdatabase
Review and analyze industry specific reports and learn how to apply this new knowledge towards improving your business or develop a business plan.
Business Model Canvas
A session to equip new and aspiring entrepreneurs with the knowledge and techniques to quickly turn their ideas into revenue generating businesses.
Cooperative Training & Coaching
A Cooperative (co-op) is a business owned by and operated for the benefit of its members. Profits or earnings are distributed among its members. 
Software Subscriptions
Access to numerous small business reports at no-cost. 
CLASSES
Range of topics covering day-to-day management of a business taught by industry experts and specialized instructors. Register for in-person and online classes at www.SmallBizAustin.org.
Class Topics:
How to get investors
How to write a business plan
Human resources basics
Interviews and hiring employees
Marketing strategies
Manage your cashflow
QuickBooks Desktop
Small business accounting
Social media best practices
Strategic pricing
Supervisory excellence
Understanding business taxes
Business Skills Certification
Participants completing any six classes taught in partnership with the University of Texas at Austin Center for Professional Education will receive a Business Skills Certificate honored with a ceremony and reception at City Hall.
EVENTS
Austin Fast Start
Austin Young Chamber Small business pitch competitions in collaboration with the Small Business Division covering specific business industries. Apply to compete for cash prizes or attend to vote for your favorite winning pitch.
Exploring Entrepreneurship
Panel discussions on general business practices and industry specific topics wit

Dear Taxpayer:

Congratulations on registering your company with the Texas Secretary of State. The company you registered
is subject to the Texas franchise tax, which my office administers. Accordingly, we have created a franchise
tax account based on the information you provided at the time of registration. The Texas franchise tax is a
privilege tax imposed on each taxable entity formed or organized in Texas or doing business in Texas. For
general information, see the Franchise Tax Overview on our website at

https: //comptroller.texas.gov/taxes/franchise/.

Your next step is to set up an online account in our Webfile system, which is quick and easy. With Webfile, you
will be able to file and pay your taxes, and keep your contact information up to date so you do not miss any
important notices. As part of the account setup process, please complete our online Franchise Tax
Accountability Questionnaire within 30 days. Just follow these steps:

* Visit https://comptroller.texas.gov/taxes/franchise/questionnaire.php (or, from www.Comptroller. Texas.Gov,
select Webfile eSystems Login) and then "Create Profile." Returning users — log in and skip the next step.

* To complete your profile setup, follow the prompts and receive an email with a validation link. Your profile is
now ready for login.

* After logging in, scroll down to Popular Services and select "Complete Franchise Tax Accountability
Questionnaire."

* Enter your taxpayer number and select "Continue."

¢ Enter your Webfile number from this letter and select "Continue."

* Complete the Franchise Tax Accountability Questionnaire.

Your company’s first franchise tax report is due on 05/15/2026. Beginning with reports due in 2024, you will
not owe a franchise tax report if your company’s total revenue is at or under the no tax due threshold, but you
must still file a Public Information Report or Ownership Information Report. We will send you a reminder with
filing instructions before the due date.

Customer service is my top priority, and my staff is ready to help you with questions related to your business’s
state tax responsibilities. Visit our agency website, www.Comptroller. Texas.Goyv, to find publications, answers
to frequently asked questions, tax rules, electronic reporting options and more. If you have any questions,
please contact us at https://comptroller.texas.gov/about/contact/.

| appreciate the work you do and the contributions you make to Texas. | wish you the best of luck in all your
business endeavors.

Sincere

📝 Notes
Oct 2, 2025
Meeting Oct 2, 2025 at 14:58 CDT
Meeting records Transcript 
Summary
Alyshia Ledlie, Micah Lindsey, and John Skelton discussed various operational and strategic topics, including the benefits of using Google Cloud due to potential free credits, the strategic importance of acquiring accelerator funding, and Alyshia's involvement with ML Commons. Additionally, Alyshia shared her success in hiring a new part-time employee for Leora, her plans to set up website data analytics for Leora, and her focus on Airbnb properties to fund the company. Chandra Srivastava and Alyshia discussed the specialized language in academic fields, insights from Startup Grind, and the company's ownership structure as a women and minority-owned business, which could lead to grants. Alyshia also created a to-do list to unblock Micah, and John Skelton offered his support with manual labor for the Airbnb properties.
Details
Meeting Logistics and Greetings Alyshia Ledlie initiated the meeting and addressed camera and screen setup issues, while Micah Lindsey mentioned that the official Thursday meeting might have been canceled. Alyshia offered to create a new, repeating meeting, and the participants exchanged greetings, with John Skelton joining later (00:00:00).
Cloud Service Discussion Micah Lindsey suggested using Google Cloud, believing it makes sense for their needs, especially after realizing they might require more CPU cores based on conversations with Chad GPT (00:00:00). Alyshia Ledlie confirmed the possibility of obtaining $2,000 in free Google Cloud credits through Tech Soup, and Micah also noted the availability of $25,000 in Azure credits for one year. They discussed the significant jump in Google Cloud credits if they receive funding, from $2,000 to $350,000, which made Google Cloud seem like a favorable option (00:01:25) (00:03:37).
Funding and Accelerator Insights Alyshia Ledlie noted that acquiring accelerator funding could significantly ease operations and mentioned that they might be able to secure such funding, which should be pursued (00:02:29). She also recalled Tara's advice that they could apply for compute resources directly rather than solely relying on accelerators, indicating they have not yet sent in those applications (00:04:28).
ML Commons Participation Alyshia Ledlie shared her involvement with ML Commons, an open-source group focused on ML-based automation and backend data, and offered to add Micah Lindsey to relevant events on the Integrity Studio calendar (00:02:29) (00:06:40). She explained that while many discussions are beyond her depth, she primarily learns by listening and contributes most effectively in the risk management and measurement chat (00:05:36) (00:07:56). Alyshia humorously recounted how she gained access to ML Commons by highlighting past Facebook projects, which impressed the organization (00:06:40).
Philosophical and Technical Discussions Chandra Srivastava and Alyshia Ledlie discussed the specialized language used in certain academic and technical fields, viewing it as a barrier to entry. Alyshia highlighted the unexpected relevance of philosophy PhDs in metaontology and diffusion mathematics for current tech roles, particularly in multimodal neural networks, suggesting a shift in valuable skills within the industry (00:09:05).
Leora Employee Acquisition Alyshia Ledlie successfully found a new employee for Leora, a social worker from Capitol City Village, who will work part-time while still in school (00:10:11). Alyshia emphasized the strategic importance of this hire for Leora's scaling efforts and for freeing up Monica's time, which ultimately benefits Integrity Studio (00:11:42). Chandra Srivastava acknowledged the value of a motivated grad student, and Alyshia highlighted the academic willingness to work for deferred benefits (00:11:42).
Website Data Analytics Alyshia Ledlie mentioned plans to set up data analytics on Leora's website once she gains access, similar to setups she has done for other organizations and her blog. She noted that integrating analytics differs significantly between owning a website and using platforms like Wix or Web Flow, as platforms often charge extra for such functionalities. Chandra Srivastava expressed interest in observing Alyshia's setup process for future reference (00:12:40).
Personal Workload and Company Funding Alyshia Ledlie informed the team that she would be focusing on her Airbnb properties for the next 48 hours, as this is currently the primary method of funding their company. She explained that events like ACL and F1 create significant rental opportunities, which allow them to cover tools and potentially pay salaries. Chandra Srivastava encouraged Alyshia to prioritize this work without apology (00:17:23) (00:20:19).

Data Usage Agreement
Between and Integrity Studio LLC
Effective Date: Date
This Data Usage Agreement ("Agreement") is entered into between Person, represented here by Person ("Data Provider") and Integrity Studio LLC, represented here by Alyshia Ledlie ("Data User").
1. Purpose of Agreement
The Data Provider hereby engages the Data User to provide compliance and operational consulting services, which require access to certain confidential data and authorization to act on Leora’s behalf in submitting filings and managing records within various systems and agencies, including but not limited to:
[Place Holder For Client Systems]

This Agreement defines the terms under which the Data User is permitted to access, use, transmit, and submit the Data Provider's data to these systems.
2. Definitions
Data: All information, regardless of format, provided by the Data Provider to the Data User under this Agreement.
Confidential Information: Any data or information disclosed by one party to the other, whether orally or in writing, that is designated as confidential or that, by its nature, would reasonably be understood to be confidential.
3. Permitted Use of Data 
The Data Provider expressly authorizes The Data User to:
Prepare, submit, and update filings and applications through TULIP and any related licensing or credentialing portals maintained by HHSC or HHSCA.
Communicate with HHSC, HHSCA, and related regulatory bodies regarding such filings.
Receive and handle communications or notifications relating to the status of applications, renewals, or compliance matters.
Sign or submit documentation in the course of the above activities, provided such actions are limited to administrative functions and do not involve legal representation or certification of clinical compliance without The Data Provider’s prior written consent.
4. Data Access and Usage
The Data User may access and use the following categories of data solely for the purposes outlined in Section 3:
Facility license information, credentials, and ownership details
Staffing rosters, qualifications, and provider credentials
Policy and procedure documents related to regulatory compliance
Patient census and service area documentation as required for filings
Electronic communications with state agencies
Integrity Studio agrees not to access, use, disclose, or retain any data outside of the scope of this Agreement, and only as necessary to perform its obligations.
5. Confidentiality
Each Party agrees to maintain the confidentiality of all non-public information exchanged in the course of this Agreement. The Data User shall treat all non-public Data as Confidential Information and shall not disclose, transmit, or otherwise make available the Data to any third party without the express written consent of the Data Provider. This obligation survives the termination of the Agreement.
6. Data Security 
The Data User shall implement and maintain appropriate technical and organizational measures to ensure the security of the Data, including protection against unauthorized or unlawful processing and against accidental loss, destruction, or damage. These measures shall include, but not be limited to:
Access controls and authentication mechanisms.
Implement and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of The Data Provider’s data.
Ensure that any staff, subcontractors, or agents with access to The Data Provider’s data are trained and contractually bound to adhere to the terms of this Agreement.
7. Data Retention and Deletion
The Data User shall retain the Data only for as long as necessary to fulfill the permitted purposes outlined in Section 4 of this Agreement. Upon termination of this Agreement or completion of the permitted purposes, the Data User shall securely delete or return all Data to the Data Provider, as instructed by the Data Provider.
8. Compliance with Laws and Regulations
The Data User shall:
Comply with all applicable federal and Texas privacy and data protection laws, including but not limited to HIPAA, the Texas Medical Records Privacy Act (TMRPA), and the Texas Health and Safety Code.
Comply with all other applicable laws, regulations, and industry standards related to data privacy and security, including but not limited to the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA).
9. Breach Notification
In the event of a data breach or any unauthorized access, use, or disclosure of the Data, the Data User shall notify the Data Provider immediately, but no later than 48 hours, after becoming aware of the breach. The notification shall include:
Nature of the breach.
Data affected.
Steps taken to mitigate the breach.
Contact information for further inquiries.
10. Indemnification
Each Party agrees to indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the other Party from and against any claims, damages, liabilities, costs, and expenses (including reasona

5900 BALCONES DR STE 100 0806120567

Dear Taxpayer:

Congratulations on registering your company with the Texas Secretary of State. The company you registered
is subject to the Texas franchise tax, which my office administers. Accordingly, we have created a franchise
tax account based on the information you provided at the time of registration. The Texas franchise tax is a
privilege tax imposed on each taxable entity formed or organized in Texas or doing business in Texas. For
general information, see the Franchise Tax Overview on our website at

https: //comptroller.texas.gov/taxes/franchise/.

Your next step is to set up an online account in our Webfile system, which is quick and easy. With Webfile, you
will be able to file and pay your taxes, and keep your contact information up to date so you do not miss any
important notices. As part of the account setup process, please complete our online Franchise Tax
Accountability Questionnaire within 30 days. Just follow these steps:

* Visit https://comptroller.texas.gov/taxes/franchise/questionnaire.php (or, from www.Comptroller. Texas.Gov,
select Webfile eSystems Login) and then "Create Profile." Returning users — log in and skip the next step.

* To complete your profile setup, follow the prompts and receive an email with a validation link. Your profile is
now ready for login.

* After logging in, scroll down to Popular Services and select "Complete Franchise Tax Accountability
Questionnaire."

* Enter your taxpayer number and select "Continue."

¢ Enter your Webfile number from this letter and select "Continue."

* Complete the Franchise Tax Accountability Questionnaire.

Your company’s first franchise tax report is due on 05/15/2026. Beginning with reports due in 2024, you will
not owe a franchise tax report if your company’s total revenue is at or under the no tax due threshold, but you
must still file a Public Information Report or Ownership Information Report. We will send you a reminder with
filing instructions before the due date.

Customer service is my top priority, and my staff is ready to help you with questions related to your business’s
state tax responsibilities. Visit our agency website, www.Comptroller. Texas.Goyv, to find publications, answers
to frequently asked questions, tax rules, electronic reporting options and more. If you have any questions,
please contact us at https://comptroller.texas.gov/about/contact/.

| appreciate the work you do and the contributions you make to Texas. | wish you the best of luck in all your
business endeavors.

Sincere

ier ae
0008244

(b) Any event which causes the Company’s business to become unlawful;

the occurrence of any other event that terminates the continued membership of a
member of the Company; or 
(d) Any other event causing dissolution of the Company under applicable state laws.
1.4. CONTINUANCE OF COMPANY. In the event of an occurrence described in Section 1.3(c),
the Company will expire and may be administratively dissolved.
1.5. BUSINESS PURPOSE. The Company will conduct any lawful business deemed appropriate in
carrying out the Company’s objectives.
1.6. PRINCIPAL PLACE OF BUSINESS.  The Company’s principal place of business will be
stated in the formation documents, or as later selected by the member.
1.7. THE MEMBER. The name and residential address of the sole member is listed in Certification
of Member section of this agreement.
Single Member Operating Agreement – Page 1 of 6              

1.8. ADMISSION OF ADDITIONAL MEMBERS. Additional members may only be admitted to
the Company through a Certificate of New Membership issuance by the company of new
interest in the Company or as otherwise provided in this agreement.
ARTICLE II
Capital Contributions
2.1. INITIAL CONTRIBUTIONS. The member will initially contribute capital to the Company, as
described in Exhibit 1 attached to this agreement. The agreed total value of such property and
cash is ____________________________.
2.2. ADDITIONAL CONTRIBUTIONS. Except as provided in ARTICLE 6.2, no member will be
obligated to make any additional contribution to the Company's capital.
ARTICLE III
Profits, Losses and Distributions
3.1. PROFITS/LOSSES. For financial accounting and tax purposes, the Company's net profits or
net losses will be determined on an annual basis. These profits and losses will be allocated to
the member as set forth in this agreement below, as amended, and in accordance with Treasury
Regulation 1.704-1.
3.2. DISTRIBUTIONS. The member will determine and distribute available funds annually or as
they see fit. “Available funds” refers to the net cash of the Company available after expenses
and  liabilities  are  paid.  Upon  liquidation  of  the  Company,  distributions  will  be  made  in
accordance with the positive capital account balances or pursuant to Treasury Regulation 1.704-
l(b)(2)(ii)(b) (2). To the extent the member has a negative capital account balance, there will be
a qualified income offset, as set forth in Treasury Regulation 1.704-l(b)(2)(ii)(d).
ARTICLE IV
Management
4.1. MANAGEMENT OF THE BUSINESS.  The member is responsible for the  management of
the Company.  
4.2. MEMBERS. The liability of the member will be limited according to state law. 
4.3. POWERS OF  MEMB ERS. The member is authorized on the Company's behalf to make
decisions as to: 
(a) the sale, development, lease, or other disposition of the Company's assets; 
(b) the purchase or other acquisition of other assets; 
(c) the management of all or any part of the Company's assets; 
(d) the borrowing of money and the granting of security interests in the Company’s
assets; 
(e) the pre-payment, refinancing, or extension of any loan affecting the Company’s
assets;

(f) the compromise or release of any of the Company's claims or debts; and 
(g) the  employment  of  persons,  firms,  or  corporations  for  the  operation  and
management of the Company's business.
The member is further authorized to execute and deliver:
(w) all contracts, conveyances, assignments leases, sub-leases, franchise agreements,
licensing agreements, management contracts and maintenance contracts covering
or affecting Company assets; 
(x) all checks, drafts, and other orders for the payment of the Company's funds; 
(y) all promissory notes, loans, security agreements, and other similar documents;
and 
(z) all other instruments of any other kind relating to the Company's affairs.
4.4. NOMINEE. Title to the Company's assets must be held in the Company's name or in the name

member has the  power to enter into a nominee agreement with any such person, and such

schema.text:
Tab 1
Data Usage Agreement
Between Leora Health LLC and Integrity Studio LLC
Effective Date: 
This Data Usage Agreement ("Agreement") is entered into between Leora Health LLC, represented here by Monica Herrera Monica Herrera ("Data Provider") and Integrity Studio LLC, represented here by Alyshia Ledlie ("Data User").
1. Purpose of Agreement
The Data Provider hereby engages the Data User to provide compliance and operational consulting services, which require access to certain confidential data and authorization to act on Leora’s behalf in submitting filings and managing records within various systems and agencies, including but not limited to:
TULIP (Texas Unified Licensure Information Portal)

Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC)

Texas Health and Human Services Commission Access (HHSCA)

This Agreement defines the terms under which the Data User is permitted to access, use, transmit, and submit the Data Provider's data to these systems.
2. Definitions
Data: All information, regardless of format, provided by the Data Provider to the Data User under this Agreement.
Confidential Information: Any data or information disclosed by one party to the other, whether orally or in writing, that is designated as confidential or that, by its nature, would reasonably be understood to be confidential.
3. Permitted Use of Data
The Data Provider expressly authorizes The Data User to:
Prepare, submit, and update filings and applications through TULIP and any related licensing or credentialing portals maintained by HHSC or HHSCA.
Communicate with HHSC, HHSCA, and related regulatory bodies regarding such filings.
Receive and handle communications or notifications relating to the status of applications, renewals, or compliance matters.
Sign or submit documentation in the course of the above activities, provided such actions are limited to administrative functions and do not involve legal representation or certification of clinical compliance without The Data Provider’s prior written consent.
4. Data Access and Usage
The Data User may access and use the following categories of data solely for the purposes outlined in Section 3:
Facility license information, credentials, and ownership details
Staffing rosters, qualifications, and provider credentials
Policy and procedure documents related to regulatory compliance
Patient census and service area documentation as required for filings
Electronic communications with state agencies
Integrity Studio agrees not to access, use, disclose, or retain any data outside of the scope of this Agreement, and only as necessary to perform its obligations.
5. Confidentiality
Each Party agrees to maintain the confidentiality of all non-public information exchanged in the course of this Agreement. The Data User shall treat all non-public Data as Confidential Information and shall not disclose, transmit, or otherwise make available the Data to any third party without the express written consent of the Data Provider. This obligation survives the termination of the Agreement.
6. Data Security 
The Data User shall implement and maintain appropriate technical and organizational measures to ensure the security of the Data, including protection against unauthorized or unlawful processing and against accidental loss, destruction, or damage. These measures shall include, but not be limited to:
Access controls and authentication mechanisms.
Implement and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of The Data Provider’s data.
Ensure that any staff, subcontractors, or agents with access to The Data Provider’s data are trained and contractually bound to adhere to the terms of this Agreement.
7. Data Retention and Deletion
The Data User shall retain the Data only for as long as necessary to fulfill the permitted purposes outlined in Section 4 of this Agreement. Upon termination of this Agreement or completion of the permitted purposes, the Data User shall securely delete or return all Data to the Data Provider, as instructed by the Data Provider.
8. Compliance with Laws and Regulations
The Data User shall:
Comply with all applicable federal and Texas privacy and data protection laws, including but not limited to HIPAA, the Texas Medical Records Privacy Act (TMRPA), and the Texas Health and Safety Code.
Comply with all other applicable laws, regulations, and industry standards related to data privacy and security, including but not limited to the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA).
9. Breach Notification
In the event of a data breach or any unauthorized access, use, or disclosure of the Data, the Data User shall notify the Data Provider immediately, but no later than 48 hours, after becoming aware of the breach. The notification shall include:
Nature of the breach.
Data affected.
Steps taken to mitigate the breach.
Contact information for further inquiries.
10. Indemni

schema.text:
OPERATING AGREEMENT OF
Leora Home Health LLC

This Operating Agreement (the "Agreement") is made effective as of September 20th, 2024, by
and between EnsoCo LLC, a Delaware limited liability company, and ARASI LLC, a Nevada
limited liability company (collectively, the “Members”, for the purpose of forming a Texas limited
liability company known as Leora Home Health LLC (the “Company’).

The Members, intending to be legally bound, agree as follows:

ARTICLE |: Formation

1. Formation of LLC: The Members hereby form a limited liability company under the laws
of the State of Texas pursuant to and in accordance with the Texas Business
Organizations Code (the “Code’).

2. Name: The name of the limited liability company shall be Leora Home Health LLC.

3. Principal Office: The principal office of the Company is located at 817 Waterfall Way,
Austin, Texas, or such other location as may be determined by the Members.

4. Registered Agent: The registered agent for the Company in the State of Texas shall be
Registered Agents Inc. 5900 Balcones Drive STE 100, TRAVIS COUNTY, Austin, TX,
78731, USA.

5. Term: The term of the Company shall commence on the filing of the Certificate of
Formation with the Texas Secretary of State and shall continue until terminated in
accordance with this Agreement.

ARTICLE II: Purpose

The purpose of the Company is to engage in any lawful business or activity for which limited
liability companies may be formed under the laws of the State of Texas, with a primary focus on
providing home healthcare services,


ARTICLE III: Ownership and Capital Contributions

1. Ownership Percentages: Each Member's ownership interest in the Company shall be
as follows:

a.
b.

EnsoCo LLC: 50%
ARASI LLC: 50%

2. Capital Contributions

a.

Proportional Contributions: Each Member shall make capital contributions in
proportion to their ownership percentage on the first Friday of every month by
making additional cash contributions to the Company’s bank account, ensuring
that contributions remain aligned with each Member's ownership percentage.
Imbalance in Contributions: If a Member fails to make their proportional
contribution, the imbalance will be recorded and accounted for. The percentage
adjustment to ownership will not be based on a single month’s missed
contribution but rather will reflect the total capital contributions made by each
Member over the entire time contributions have been paid into the Company.
Proportional Adjustment: Ownership percentages will be adjusted to reflect the
cumulative total contributions made by each Member. If a Member
consistently contributes less than their proportional share over time, their
ownership percentage will be reduced accordingly. If the imbalance is corrected,
ownership percentages will be readjusted to reflect the total amount contributed
by each Member.

Permanent Adjustment After 3 Months: If the imbalance in cumulative
contributions is not resolved within three (3) months, the temporary adjustment
will become permanent, and ownership percentages will be permanently reduced
based on the total contributions made to date.

Service Contributions: Each Member will contribute services to the Company,
referred to as “sweat equity.” The value of services shall not alter ownership
percentages or require compensation unless otherwise agreed by the Members.

3. Funding Future Needs

2/13

a.

Proportional Contributions: In the event that additional capital is required, each
Member will contribute funds in proportion to their ownership percentage unless
otherwise agreed.

Initial and Ongoing Contributions: The Members agree to contribute an initial
lump sum to fund the business and then reinvest profits before requiring
additional capital. Additional capital needs will be addressed with lump sum
contributions as necessary.

ARTICLE IV: Employee Equity Grants and Dilution
Provisions

1. Issuance of Employee Equity

a. Authority to Grant Equity: The Company is authorized to issue equity grants to

employees as part of their compensation.
leh

Vesting Schedule and Terms: Employee equity grants shall be subject to the
vesting schedule as defined in separate Equity Compensation Agreements.

c. Employee Equity Pool: The specific percentage allocated to each employee will
be outlined in their Equity Compensation Agreement.
rh

Impact on Existing Members
a. Dilution of Existing Ownership: The issuance of new equity to employees will
result in dilution of the ownership percentages of the existing Members (EnsoCo
LLC and ARASI LLC). No dilution protection is provided to the existing Members

unless agreed upon in writing. Dilution protection for employees is subject to the
definition in their Equity Compensation Agreements.

b. Approval of Equity Grants: All new equity issuances to employees must be
approved by the Members based on their ownership percentages. Each
Member's vote on approving new equity grants will be proportional to their
ownership interest in the Company.

"""
Represents an EC2 Elastic Block Storage Volume
"""
from boto.resultset import ResultSet
from boto.ec2.tag import Tag
from boto.ec2.ec2object import TaggedEC2Object


class Volume(TaggedEC2Object):
    """
    Represents an EBS volume.

    :ivar id: The unique ID of the volume.
    :ivar create_time: The timestamp of when the volume was created.
    :ivar status: The status of the volume.
    :ivar size: The size (in GB) of the volume.
    :ivar snapshot_id: The ID of the snapshot this volume was created
        from, if applicable.
    :ivar attach_data: An AttachmentSet object.
    :ivar zone: The availability zone this volume is in.
    :ivar type: The type of volume (standard or consistent-iops)
    :ivar iops: If this volume is of type consistent-iops, this is
        the number of IOPS provisioned (10-300).
    :ivar encrypted: True if this volume is encrypted.
    """

    def __init__(self, connection=None):
        super(Volume, self).__init__(connection)
        self.id = None
        self.create_time = None
        self.status = None
        self.size = None
        self.snapshot_id = None
        self.attach_data = None
        self.zone = None
        self.type = None
        self.iops = None
        self.encrypted = None

    def __repr__(self):
        return 'Volume:%s' % self.id

    def startElement(self, name, attrs, connection):
        retval = super(Volume, self).startElement(name, attrs, connection)
        if retval is not None:
            return retval
        if name == 'attachmentSet':
            self.attach_data = AttachmentSet()
            return self.attach_data
        elif name == 'tagSet':
            self.tags = ResultSet([('item', Tag)])
            return self.tags
        else:
            return None

    def endElement(self, name, value, connection):
        if name == 'volumeId':
            self.id = value
        elif name == 'createTime':
            self.create_time = value
        elif name == 'status':
            if value != '':
                self.status = value
        elif name == 'size':
            self.size = int(value)
        elif name == 'snapshotId':
            self.snapshot_id = value
        elif name == 'availabilityZone':
            self.zone = value
        elif name == 'volumeType':
            self.type = value
        elif name == 'iops':
            self.iops = int(value)
        elif name == 'encrypted':
            self.encrypted = (value.lower() == 'true')
        else:
            setattr(self, name, value)

    def _update(self, updated):
        self.__dict__.update(updated.__dict__)

    def update(self, validate=False, dry_run=False):
        """
        Update the data associated with this volume by querying EC2.

        :type validate: bool
        :param validate: By default, if EC2 returns no data about the
                         volume the update method returns quietly.  If
                         the validate param is True, however, it will
                         raise a ValueError exception if no data is
                         returned from EC2.
        """
        # Check the resultset since Eucalyptus ignores the volumeId param
        unfiltered_rs = self.connection.get_all_volumes(
            [self.id],
            dry_run=dry_run
        )
        rs = [x for x in unfiltered_rs if x.id == self.id]
        if len(rs) > 0:
            self._update(rs[0])
        elif validate:
            raise ValueError('%s is not a valid Volume ID' % self.id)
        return self.status

    def delete(self, dry_run=False):
        """
        Delete this EBS volume.

        :rtype: bool
        :return: True if successful
        """
        return self.connection.delete_volume(self.id, dry_run=dry_run)

WHEREAS, pursuant to the provisions of the Agreement, amendments require the approval of the Members;
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Members agree as follows:
1. AMENDMENT TO THE AGREEMENT
1.1 Change in Equity Distribution
Previously, ARASI LLC held 41.18%, EnsoCo LLC 41.18%, and Ashley Kitzko directly held 17.64% equity in the Company.
The Amendment
transfers all shares previously directly held by Ashley Kitzko to Enerra LLC, a manager-owned sole proprietorship LLC owned by Ashley Kitzko
removes EnsoCo LLC from any and all equity ownership and management in Leora Home Health LLC
redistributes EnsoCo’s shares between Enerra LLC and ARASI LLC as follows:

Enerra LLC :49%
Designated Controlling Person: Ashley Kitzko
1.2 Definition of Equity Member
The "Equity Member" classification refers to Members who hold an equity and debt stake in the Company and have voting rights in decision-making; this equity is subject to dilution.
The current Equity Members and their respective ownership percentages are:
ARASI LLC: 51%
Enerra LLC: 49%
2. EFFECT OF AMENDMENT
2.1 In the event of any conflict between the terms of this Amendment and any previous operating agreements or articles of incorporation, the terms of this Amendment shall govern.

AMENDMENT TO THE OPERATING AGREEMENT OF LEORA HOME HEALTH LLC

This Amendment to the Operating Agreement (the "Amendment") of Leora Home Health LLC
(the "Company") is made and entered into as of [Date], by and between the Members of the
Company, as identified in the Operating Agreement originally executed on September 20, 2024.

RECITALS WHEREAS, the Members executed an Operating Agreement governing the
management, ownership, and operations of the Company;

WHEREAS, the Members wish to amend the provisions related to the ownership of intellectual
property to clarify that software not specifically created for Leora Home Health LLC shall not be
considered the property of the Company;

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and covenants contained herein
and in the Operating Agreement, the Members agree as follows:

AMENDMENT

1. Modification of Article XV: Ownership of Intellectual Property
Article XV of the Operating Agreement is hereby amended and restated as follows:
Ownership of Intellectual Property:

o All intellectual property created, developed, or acquired by the Members in
connection with the business of the Company, including but not limited to
trademarks, copyrights, patents, software, and business processes, shall be the
sole property of the Company if it is specifically created, developed, or acquired
by the Members for use by the Company.

°o Notwithstanding the foregoing, any software developed, created, or acquired by a
Member that is not specifically developed, created, or acquired for Leora Home
Health LLC shall not be considered the property of the Company. Ownership of
such software shall remain with the Member or entity that developed or acquired
it. This includes, but is not limited to, software developed by a Member for other
business ventures, unrelated projects, or companies owned by a Member outside
of Leora Home Health LLC.

o Inthe event that software originally developed outside the scope of Leora Home
Health LLC is later incorporated into the Company’s business operations, the
terms of use, licensing, or transfer of ownership shall be subject to a separate
written agreement between the Members.

2. Effect of Amendment

o Except as expressly modified by this Amendment, all terms and conditions of the
original Operating Agreement shall remain in full force and effect.

o If any provision of this Amendment conflicts with the terms of the original
Operating Agreement, the provisions of this Amendment shall control.

3. Governing Law

© This Amendment shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the
laws of the State of Texas.

SIGNATURES IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned Members have executed this
Amendment as of the date first written above.

Company Formation
1.1. FORMATION. The  member  has  formed  a  Limited  Liability  Company  (the  "Company")

1.3. TERM. The Company will continue perpetually unless:
(a) The sole member resolves to dissolve; 
(b) Any event which causes the Company’s business to become unlawful; 
(c) The death, resignation, expulsion, bankruptcy, retirement of the sole member or
the occurrence of any other event that terminates the continued membership of a
member of the Company; or 
(d) Any other event causing dissolution of the Company under applicable state laws.
1.4. CONTINUANCE OF COMPANY. In the event of an occurrence described in Section 1.3(c),
the Company will expire and may be administratively dissolved.
1.5. BUSINESS PURPOSE. The Company will conduct any lawful business deemed appropriate in
carrying out the Company’s objectives.

Capital Contributions
2.1. INITIAL CONTRIBUTIONS. The member will initially contribute capital to the Company, as
described in Exhibit 1 attached to this agreement. The agreed total value of such property and
cash is ____________________________.
2.2. ADDITIONAL CONTRIBUTIONS. Except as provided in ARTICLE 6.2, no member will be
obligated to make any additional contribution to the Company's capital.
ARTICLE III
Profits, Losses and Distributions
3.1. PROFITS/LOSSES. For financial accounting and tax purposes, the Company's net profits or
net losses will be determined on an annual basis. These profits and losses will be allocated to
the member as set forth in this agreement below, as amended, and in accordance with Treasury
Regulation 1.704-1.
3.2. DISTRIBUTIONS. The member will determine and distribute available funds annually or as
they see fit. “Available funds” refers to the net cash of the Company available after expenses
and  liabilities  are  paid.  Upon  liquidation  of  the  Company,  distributions  will  be  made  in
accordance with the positive capital account balances or pursuant to Treasury Regulation 1.704-
l(b)(2)(ii)(b) (2). To the extent the member has a negative capital account balance, there will be
a qualified income offset, as set forth in Treasury Regulation 1.704-l(b)(2)(ii)(d).
ARTICLE IV
Management
4.1. MANAGEMENT OF THE BUSINESS.  The member is responsible for the  management of
the Company.  
4.2. MEMBERS. The liability of the member will be limited according to state law. 
4.3. POWERS OF  MEMB ERS. The member is authorized on the Company's behalf to make

(a) the sale, development, lease, or other disposition of the Company's assets; 
(b) the purchase or other acquisition of other assets;

assets; 
(e) the pre-payment, refinancing, or extension of any loan affecting the Company’s
assets;

Tab 1
Data Usage Agreement
Between and Integrity Studio LLC
Effective Date: Aug 26, 2025
This Data Usage Agreement ("Agreement") is entered into between Inspired Movement LLC, represented here by Favian Bustos ("Data Provider") and Integrity Studio LLC, represented here by Alyshia Ledlie ("Data User").
1. Purpose of Agreement
The Data Provider hereby engages the Data User to provide compliance, marketing, and operational consulting services, which require access to certain confidential data and authorization to act on behalf of the Data Provider in submitting filings, managing records of client and financial data, within various systems and agencies, including but not limited to:
Google Analytics
Facebook Analytics 
Telegram
Any and all online presence management systems, including but not limited to:
Web Hosting Service
Domain Management
Web management services
Any separate CRM or CMS systems
Any and all internal corporate data, including but not limited to:
Accounting Management Systems (e.g. Quickbooks)
Google Workspace
Physical Documents
Cloud-based document systems, such as Google Drive or DropBox

This Agreement defines the terms under which the Data User is permitted to access, use, transmit, and submit the Data Provider's data from or to these systems.
2. Definitions
Data: All information, regardless of format, provided by the Data Provider to the Data User under this Agreement.
Confidential Information: Any data or information disclosed by one party to the other, whether orally or in writing, that is designated as confidential or that, by its nature, would reasonably be understood to be confidential.
3. Permitted Use of Data 
The Data Provider expressly authorizes The Data User to:
Prepare, submit, and update filings and applications through TULIP and any related licensing or credentialing portals maintained by HHSC or HHSCA.
Communicate with HHSC, HHSCA, and related regulatory bodies regarding such filings.
Receive and handle communications or notifications relating to the status of applications, renewals, or compliance matters.
Sign or submit documentation in the course of the above activities, provided such actions are limited to administrative functions and do not involve legal representation or certification of clinical compliance without The Data Provider’s prior written consent.
4. Data Access and Usage
The Data User may access and use the following categories of data solely for the purposes outlined in Section 3:
Data Management and Acquisition Services
Web Management Support and Optimization
SEO optimization
Providing Marketing Data & Campaign planning
 Streamlining or automating operational processes, as expressly requested by Data Provider
Integrity Studio agrees not to access, use, disclose, or retain any data outside of the scope of this Agreement, and only as necessary to perform its obligations.
5. Confidentiality
Each Party agrees to maintain the confidentiality of all non-public information exchanged in the course of this Agreement. The Data User shall treat all non-public Data as Confidential Information and shall not disclose, transmit, or otherwise make available the Data to any third party without the express written consent of the Data Provider. This obligation survives the termination of the Agreement.
6. Data Security

The AI Impact Navigator Survey
The AI Impact Navigator Survey looks at your AI impact across 4 dimensions: 
Effective AI and community impact
Embrace transparency and accountability in AI to foster trust and enhance community engagement, as you navigate its evolving impacts and ethical considerations.
Customer experience and consumer rights
Enhance customer experiences with AI by responsibly leveraging data, ensuring privacy and fairness while balancing competitive advantage and consumer rights.
Workforce and productivity
Leverage AI to enhance productivity and innovation while addressing the challenges of job displacement, regulatory compliance, and skill adaptation in an evolving technological landscape.
Social licence and corporate transparency
Embrace transparency in your AI initiatives, continuously monitor their impact, and engage with communities to demonstrate accountability.
Each dimension has 5 indicators which you can use to score your company’s AI readiness. We’ve included questions you can ask to prompt your thinking when assessing your company, as well as examples of how you can measure and monitor your readiness against each indicator. You can use these examples as they are, take inspiration from them, or create ones of similar robustness that fit your company’s context. 
Key to readiness levels
Poor
Understanding and delivery of AI impact is inadequate.
Fair
Understanding, delivery and measurement of AI impact is progressing but lacks consistency.
Good
Understanding, delivery and measurement of AI Impact is positive and consistent.
Very good
Understanding, delivery and measurement of AI Impact is very positive. We verify our AI Impact but do not publicly disclose it.
Excellent 
Understanding and delivery of AI Impact is very positive. We verify our AI Impact and publicly disclose it.
Key to each dimension’s total score
5–11	Lower readiness
12–16	Medium readiness
17–21	Higher readiness
22+	Best practice
Effective AI and community impact
Company readiness
Indicator 1: We share with the public how we use AI in a way that is accessible and clear.
This indicator is about transparency. When assessing your company, ask:
Is information easily available in a format that is accessible, and described in simple language?
Is AI’s role in the company clearly articulated?
In what ways can you see that the information is accessed, and what does it indicate?

Indicator 2: Our AI initiatives and investments deliver the desired Return on Investment and outcomes.
This indicator is about value delivery. When assessing your company, ask:

Increase in revenue attributable to AI initiatives
Indicator 3: We actively monitor and respond to the communities’ sentiment towards our adoption of AI.
This is indicator is about receptiveness. When assessing your company, ask:
Does your company track and engage with community on how your adoption of AI affects them?
How does it factor into your decision making?

Indicator 4: We have mechanisms to adapt our AI governance continuously and address specific concerns identified via community feedback or perspectives.
This indicator is about adaptability. When assessing your company, ask:

schema.text:
GET STARTED WITH YOUR
CRM REPORT
If you are looking for a system to organize your contacts, solidify a sales process, and automate some of your ongoing tasks then you need a CRM (customer relationship management) solution. This template provides you with the basics of a CRM. It's the perfect place to start if you aren't quite ready for a full-blown CRM with advanced features. This mini-CRM automatically saves changes so you will never lose data. To get started, just enter your contacts manually or copy and paste existing data into this sheet.
How to use this template
1.0 When setting up this mini-CRM for the first time, go to the "Settings" tab to define categories for characteristics such as Contact Type for People or Stage for Opportunities 2.0 Keep the CRM up-to-date by updating or adding rows as you engage with "People", "Companies", and "Opportunities"
 3.0 Use the CRM to plan your daily, weekly, and monthly goals. The "Dashboard" provides a summary of how your sales pipeline is doing to help you decide what to address next.
Let's walk you through the tabs listed at the bottom of this sheet.
Dashboard
Think of the Dashboard tab as your control panel for your opportunities. You'll see the following information:

- The total value of all your opportunities
- Total number of People, Companies, and Opportunities in this CRM
- The number of Opportunities by stage and the value of Opportunities by stage

This is a great place to start planning your daily goals!
People
A Person is someone you have already qualified to do business with. They may be a current customer, potential customer, or some other type of contact or relationship. This is the Person that works for a Company you want to do business with.
Companies
A Company is an organizational entity that you are either doing business with now, or may be doing business with soon. We like to think of the Company as the building that the People you are dealing with work in. The Company record is the top level record that we relate other records such as People or Opportunities to.
Opportunities
An Opportunity represents any kind of business development effort that you would like to track and move along through a process. You could also call an Opportunity a "deal" or a "sale". An Opportunity could represent the sale of a product, billings associated with services, or an activity that has no direct monetary value, like increasing your press coverage.
Setting
This is where you define the following items that will set the data rules in your Sheet: 

- Contact Type for People and Company         
- Stage, Status, Source, and Loss Reason for Opportunities 

You'll want to adjust this to what makes the most sense for your business process.

Details
Festival Financials and Tax Deductions Alyshia Ledlie discussed the financial outcomes of a recent festival, noting a $23,285 tax deduction from Integrity Studios' contribution and a personal deduction of $2,500 (00:10:54). She explained that while no direct payment was received for their work, these deductions could be beneficial if the company generates significant profit by December (00:11:59). Alyshia Ledlie plans to send John Skelton the financial document prepared by Amy, who has extensive experience with non-profits, and requested John Skelton research the legality of splitting the tax deduction among individuals like Micah and Shandra (00:13:12).
Administrator Qualification Research Alyshia Ledlie is exploring the possibility of qualifying as an alternate administrator for a home healthcare company, which would allow them to use their address as the business address and be present for surveyor visits, simplifying operations for Monica and allowing Monica to take lucrative travel nurse contracts (00:18:03). Alyshia Ledlie has 13 months of experience from the Advisory Board Company that should qualify, and they are investigating if their three years as a CASA (Child Advocate Special Something), coordinating services for children in the CPS system, could also count towards the two-year administrative experience requirement for working with vulnerable populations (00:19:27) (00:24:59). If not, Alyshia Ledlie mentioned they might backdate their advisory work with Monica to meet the two-year requirement (00:24:59).
Client Business Operations and Financial Strategy Alyshia Ledlie detailed their work with Monica to reduce operating expenses for their client's home healthcare company, bringing them down from approximately $1,000 to $600-$700 per month (00:15:31). The primary goal is to help the company achieve $2,000 a month in profit by January, enabling Monica and Ashley to eventually leave their day jobs. John Skelton will research the legality of splitting the tax deduction between Micah and Chandra and check with his dad about it.

Alyshia  Ledlie is  a  technology  professional  and  entrepreneur  based  in  Austin,  Texas.  Her  online

presence, academic background, and other relevant details.
Professional Background and Employment
Founder & CTO of InventoryAI and Integrity Studio (2024–Present): In February 2024, Alyshia
Ledlie  launched  two  startup  ventures  –  InventoryAI and  Integrity  Studio(s) –  where  she  leads  as
Founder  and  Chief  Technology  Officer.  These  ventures  focus  on  automation-driven
solutions across  retail,  security,  compliance,  and  non-profit  sectors.  Under  her  leadership,  the
startups have secured multiple B2B clients and even received seed funding/accelerator interest.
She  has  forged  partnerships  with  organizations  like  HEB  (a  Texas  grocery  chain),  local  Austin
government agencies, and non-profits, reducing customer acquisition costs and contributing to the
local community.
Entrepreneur-in-Residence & Consultant at Concierge.io (2023–Present): Since February 2023,
Ledlie has served in an Entrepreneur-in-Residence/independent consultant role for Concierge.io, a
luxury travel and services platform. In this capacity, she worked on multiple projects spanning real
estate  management,  HR  risk  identification,  and  travel  data  insights/marketing.  She
designed  and  deployed  architectures  integrating  third-party  services  with  custom  solutions,
automating day-to-day operations for clients within a year.
Meta (Facebook) – Trust & Safety Engineering Leadership (2015–2023): Alyshia spent 8 years at
Facebook/Meta in technical roles focused on Trust & Safety (i.e. maintaining platform integrity and
combating abuse):

Meta’s Integrity org in Austin, she built a static-analysis and code-generation platform for managing
ML-driven integrity automation (content moderation rules, features, models). This unified
UI allowed developers and operations teams to deploy and monitor model performance and costs.

safety systems, cutting enforcement launch times by over 60%. In addition, she mentored
engineers and defined performance metrics aligned with business needs.
Technical Principal, Trust & Safety Engineering (Facebook, 2017–2021): Led the architecture and
development of scalable Trust & Safety infrastructure at Facebook. Notably, she oversaw the 
zero-error-tolerance political ad enforcement system for the 2020 U.S. election. Her initiatives
improved automation in content enforcement workflows by 44% and reduced compliance-related

General Release of Liability
Effective Date:______________________________
WHEREAS, Alvin Cheung, EnsoCo LLC, and DotFun LLC (collectively with Alvin, the “Exiting Parties”) desire to withdraw fully and permanently from Leora Home Health LLC (the “Company”) (Exiting Parties and the Company together the “Parties”);
WHEREAS, the Exiting Parties desire to divest and transfer all ownership interests, rights, and obligations in the Company, in order to pursue independent business ventures;
WHEREAS, the Remaining Members of the Company, ARASI LLC, as represented here by Monica Herrera Hernandez and Enerra LLC, as represented here by Ashley Kitzko, desire to accept such withdrawal and require the return of the Exiting Parties’ equity in order to continue the Company’s operations and expansion in the absence of the Exiting Parties’ services as co-owner and vendor;
WHEREAS, as consideration for the withdrawal and equity transfer, the Company agrees to provide the Exiting Parties with mutual releases, a promise not to sue, indemnification and hold harmless protections, and the repayment terms specified herein;
WHEREAS, all parties mutually acknowledge that this is a no-fault separation, that no wrongdoing is alleged by any party, and that the intent of this Agreement is to provide a full and final release of claims, liabilities, and obligations between them;
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein, the parties agree as follows:
1 Release and Benefits
1.1  The Company  Shall Release The Exiting Parties
Effective immediately upon execution, the Company hereby releases and forever discharges the Exiting Parties and its affiliates from liability, any and all claims, debts, demands, damages, actions, and causes of action or suits of any kind or nature whatsoever, which the Company may now have or may hereafter have, arising out of or in any way relating to any and all injuries and damages of any and every kind, to both person and property, and also any and all injuries and damages that may develop in the future, as a result of or in any way relating and not limited to the following:
Any and all business operations of the Company
Any and all liability arising from IP as defined in the Agreement “Termination of DotFun LLC” between the Exiting Parties and the Company 
Any and all fees, charges, or fines related to the operations or corporate formation of the Company
Any and all future expenses or debt incurred by the Company
Potential injuries arising from Company operations and structure may include but are not limited to:
Obligation of payment towards Worker’s Compensation Fees
Payment of Fines or filing charges to HHSC or HHSCA
Payment for ongoing expenses related to the day to day operations of the Company
Liabilities incurred as a result of lawsuits filed for or on behalf of the Company’s clients
Liabilities incurred as a result of lawsuits filed for or on behalf of the Company’s employees
Fees incurred due to dissolution of the Company
Class Action or Arbitration judgements made against the Company 
1.2  Exiting Parties Shall  Release the Company 
Effective immediately upon execution, the Exiting Parties hereby releases and discharges the Company and any and all affiliates from any and all claims, debts, demands, damages, actions, and causes of action or suits of any kind or nature whatsoever, which the Company or the Exiting Parties may now have or may hereafter have, arising out of or in any way relating to any and all injuries and damages of any and every kind, to both person and property, and also any and all injuries and damages that may develop in the future, as a result of or in any way relating to but not limited to the following:
Any and all business operations of the Exiting Parties
Any and all liability arising from IP created for or in partnership with the Company as defined in the agreement “Termination of DotFun LLC” between the Exiting Parties and the Company
Any and all fees, charges, or fines related to the operations or corporate formation of the Company
Any and all future expenses or debt incurred by the Exiting Parties 
Any and all claims to all future revenue and profit of The Company
1.3 Indemnification
 The Company shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Exiting Parties and their affiliates from and against any and all claims, demands, liabilities, losses, damages, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) arising out of or relating to:
(a) the operations, debts, contracts, obligations, or activities of the Company, whether incurred before or after the Effective Date;
 (b) any regulatory, tax, employment, or contractual obligations of the Company; and
 (c) any third-party claims, lawsuits, actions, or proceedings brought against the Exiting Parties that are based on or arise out of the Company’s business.
1.4 Mutual Indemnification
Both Parties agree to hold harmless and indemnify to the fullest extent of law any and all claim
